2026-04-16 07:51:20 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['control_module_1_led', 'control_module_2_led', 'control_module_3_led', 'control_module_4_led', 'control_module_5_led', 'control_module_6_led', 'control_module_7_led', 'control_module_8_led'] hypothesis_explanation="The system symptoms and observations indicate that all indicator LEDs (and only the LEDs themselves, not associated circuitry) in the control modules are missing. However, the circuit as designed still allows current to flow through the load (since the path through the switch bypasses the LED+resistor branch). Since none of these LEDs are presenting as 'faulty' components and have simply been physically removed, the rest of the circuit should work provided the LEDs are designed as parallel indicators and not as the only conductive path for current. The next most plausible cause is that the absence of the LEDs has physically broken or interrupted the main current path (for example, if the sockets/housings do not internally connect the circuit when an LED is absent). Thus, the actual fault may be in the LED holders (or the design of the holder circuit)--when no LED is present, the circuit is open at each control module. The real failed components are therefore the main current paths within all control module LED HOLDERS (or the holders act as required jumpers for current, and without LEDs they are all open). Thus, a hypothesis is all 8 main current paths through LED holders (lack of 'LED-holder shunt' function) are open. This physically blocks current through the whole series circuit, so no indicator LEDs or load will light up. The components to be replaced/modified are all 8 LED-holder current paths."
